"step_by_step_thinking": "The question is asking which of the given options is pierced during a posterior superior alveolar nerve block. The answer lies in understanding the anatomy of the area involved in the procedure. Posterior superior alveolar nerve block is a technique used to anesthetize the upper molars and surrounding soft tissues. It involves blocking the posterior superior alveolar nerve which arises from the maxillary division of the trigeminal nerve. The nerve then travels through the pterygopalatine fossa, passes through the infraorbital canal and enters the oral cavity through the canine fossa to innervate the upper molars. In order to block this nerve, one would need to pierce through the medial pterygoid muscle which is one of the muscles that forms part of the pterygoid plate.",
